---
import Layout from '@/layouts/Layout.astro';
import Nav from '@/components/Nav.astro';
import Footer from '@/components/Footer.astro';
import Section from '@/components/Section.astro';
import Glow from '@/components/Glow.astro';
import Eyebrow from '@/components/Eyebrow.astro';
---

<Layout
  title="Spec-driven in, evidence-backed out · Kontour AI"
  description="The design.md movement is right about half the loop. A spec constrains what an agent intends; it does nothing about what the agent claims afterward. The missing half is evidence on the way out."
>
  <Nav active="developers" />

  <Section contour size="hero" borderBottom>
    <Glow accent="gold" position="top-right" />
    <div class="container container--readable">
      <Eyebrow accent="gold">Writing</Eyebrow>
      <h1 class="product-title animate-fade-up">Spec-driven in, evidence-backed out</h1>
      <p class="hero-copy animate-fade-up delay-200">
        The design.md movement is right — and it's half a loop. Writing the
        spec down disciplines what an agent <em>intends</em>. It does nothing
        about what the agent <em>claims afterward</em>. If you've adopted
        spec-driven development and still catch "done" that isn't, this is
        why.
      </p>
    </div>
  </Section>

  <Section tone="alt" size="lg" borderBottom>
    <div class="container container--readable">
      <h2 class="section-heading">The half that works</h2>
      <p class="body measure-lg prose">
        Spec-driven in is a real improvement, and the movement deserves its
        momentum. A committed DESIGN.md gives the agent a durable statement of
        intent that survives session boundaries; it gives reviewers a fixed
        point to diff behavior against; it turns "the agent went off and did
        something" into "the agent deviated from §3." We run it ourselves —
        this site has a <a href="https://github.com/kontourai/kontourai.io/blob/main/DESIGN.md">DESIGN.md</a>,
        and the parts of our spec that matter most aren't even prose: they're
        executable checks that fail CI when copy drifts, when a banned string
        appears, or when a published artifact stops matching its source.
      </p>
      <p class="body measure-lg prose">
        But notice what a spec is: <strong>input discipline.</strong> It
        constrains the work on the way in. Then the work happens — in a long
        session, through compactions, across tool calls — and at the end the
        agent reports what it did. The spec has no opinion about that report.
      </p>
    </div>
  </Section>

  <Section size="lg" borderBottom>
    <div class="container container--readable">
      <h2 class="section-heading">The half that's missing</h2>
      <p class="body measure-lg prose">
        Every agent user has watched this moment: a long session, a compacted
        context, and the agent reports "tests pass, done" — recording the
        check it <em>remembers intending to run</em>. Not a liar; an
        unreliable narrator. The spec was followed, more or less. The claim at
        the end is the thing nothing verified.
      </p>
      <p class="body measure-lg prose">
        That's the missing half: <strong>evidence-backed out.</strong> Our
        one-line version: prompts are advice, gates are laws. A spec asks an
        agent to be careful; a gate refuses to let "done" through until the
        evidence exists. Concretely, three moves close the loop:
      </p>
      <ul class="body measure-lg prose loop-list">
        <li><strong>The claim</strong> — the agent says "tests passed." Free to say, so never what a gate checks.</li>
        <li><strong>The capture</strong> — the harness already wrote the log while the command ran: real exit codes, a tamper-evident record, never the model's narration.</li>
        <li><strong>The recompute</strong> — status derives from the evidence. Claim and capture disagree? The turn is blocked, and CI re-runs the declared checks fresh in an environment the agent never touched.</li>
      </ul>
      <p class="body measure-lg prose">
        Spec-driven in tells you what the work <em>should have been</em>.
        Evidence-backed out proves what it <em>was</em>. Either alone leaves
        the failure mode you already know: beautiful specs, unverified
        "done."
      </p>
    </div>
  </Section>

  <Section tone="alt" size="lg" borderBottom>
    <div class="container container--readable">
      <h2 class="section-heading">The worked example is this site</h2>
      <p class="body measure-lg prose">
        We won't argue this in the abstract. kontourai.io runs both halves on
        itself, and you can check every claim from the outside: the
        <a href="https://github.com/kontourai/kontourai.io/blob/main/DESIGN.md">DESIGN.md</a>
        records the spec and the enforcement chain; the
        <a href="/receipts/">receipts page</a> publishes real
        trust bundles that recompute under two validators — led by one whose
        verdict is a refusal, because green receipts prove a format and
        refusals prove a gate; and the <a href="/trust/">trust page</a> leads
        with what none of this can certify, three ways to cheat it, and who
        catches each one.
      </p>
      <p class="body measure-lg prose">
        One more line completes the picture, because memory keeps being
        offered as the answer to agent reliability: memory tells the agent
        what it knows. It doesn't verify anything on the way out either.
        <em>Kontour proves what its answers stood on.</em>
      </p>
      <div class="post-actions">
        <a href="/flow-agents/" class="btn-primary" data-umami-event="writing-specdriven-flow-agents">The engine that runs the loop →</a>
        <a href="/trust/" class="btn-ghost" data-umami-event="writing-specdriven-trust">Read the honest ceiling →</a>
      </div>
    </div>
    <p class="body measure-lg prose">
        The same architecture, applied to data instead of code:
        <a href="/writing/llm-proposes-structure-verifies/" data-umami-event="writing-specdriven-sibling">LLM proposes, structure verifies</a> —
        an extraction pipeline that refuses to promote what no gate has checked.
      </p>
    </Section>

  <Footer active="developers" />
</Layout>

<style>
  .container--readable {
    margin-inline: auto;
  }
  .section-heading {
    font-size: 1.75rem;
    margin: 0 0 1.25rem;
    color: var(--color-chalk);
  }
  .prose {
    margin: 0 0 1.5rem;
  }
  .prose a {
    color: var(--color-gold-2);
  }
  .loop-list {
    display: grid;
    gap: 0.85rem;
    padding-left: 1.25rem;
  }
  .post-actions {
    display: flex;
    flex-wrap: wrap;
    gap: 1rem;
    margin-top: 0.5rem;
  }
</style>
